<TITLE> Air France says also involved in EU Japan probe </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 PARIS, March 12 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Air France said it had been questioned like other airlines as part of a European Commission investigation into a suspected price-fixing cartel on flights to Japan. "Air France is providing the Commission with its full cooperation," it said in a statement dated March 11. A spokeswoman had declined to comment on Tuesday. European Commission trust busters on Tuesday raided the offices of several international airlines operating long-haul scheduled flights to Japan. Such inspections are a preliminary step in investigations into suspected cartels and do not necessarily mean companies are guilty of anti-competitive behaviour. Germany's Lufthansa and KLM Royal Dutch Airlines, the Dutch arm of Air France, said on Tuesday they were involved in the probe. A source at Italy's Alitalia said it too was raided. British Airways, Virgin Atlantic and Scandinavian airline SAS said they had not been raided. Spain's Iberia said its flights to Japan were operated on a code-share basis and it had no information on the investigation. Japan Airlines Corp (JAL) and All Nippon Airways Co Ltd (ANA) said on Wednesday they were not being investigated as part of an EU cartel probe. The Commission has the power to fine companies it finds guilty of involvement in a cart
